##I want you to see what's going on in Wuhan | an exclusive interview with Wuhan front-line photographers

MICRO-SIGNAL LDNL1602

This is a new media lab for more than 100 college students from all over the world. This is where I met the most stylish college photographer.

This is the new media lab for college students

It's your turn: It's Day 16 for Chen Zhuo, a photojournalist with Wuhan Changjiang daily, who was temporarily transferred to the front line of the story a year after he was transferred from his post. The day before the closure of the city, he settled his family and returned to Wuhan with his wife to celebrate the unknown and risky, unprecedented Spring Festival.

The girl who chased the hearse..

(all the videos and pictures in this article were taken by Chen Zhuo.)

The girl was crying, I was crying

Lun: Last night I saw a short video posted by friends'circle of a girl crying and chasing after an ambulance with her mother in it. Did you take this?

Chen Zhuo: Yes, this was taken outside the emergency room of the Hubei Provincial Hospital for the integration of traditional Chinese and Western medicine, also known as Xinhua Hospital. Her mother, who had COVID-19 pneumonia for four or five days, died in the emergency room. As professional journalists, we avoided taking pictures of bodies, so I didn't take the camera. But I watched the girl chase the hearse, crying out for her mother, and I made a little video on my phone. These days, seeing a lot of this, recording this is also an expression of emotion.

So many days of interviews, see too many patients die, and relatives of this separation, the heart is very, very heavy. The girl was crying, and I was crying all the time while I was filming, and you could see that the video was very shaky, and I really didn't have the heart. But I still want my circle of friends to be able to see: Wuhan, what the Hell happened?

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the day of the siege, he rushed back to Wuhan

Round: How many days is it since you started reporting this outbreak? How are the daily reports usually arranged these days? Do you run around the hospital every day, or do you do photo assignments on different topics, or do you do independent photography?

Chen Zhuo: I wasn't in the newsroom at the beginning of 2019. I was transferred to the long newspaper Group of media companies, responsible for some business activities and business. But as a professional photojournalist used to, usually encounter a good news story thematic clues, or will pay attention to. After leaving this news post, I did a special project on a mountain village primary school.

This epidemic happened to coincide with the new year, the lack of reporters, my home in Wuhan, was pulled back to do this report. But before the transfer, I started recording on January 20th.

When Zhong Nanshan told CCTV on January 20 that 14 medical staff in Wuhan had been infected and the virus would spread from person to person, I knew this was something special. Just like SARS in 2003, it is a very important historical event. I've been a journalist for more than 10 years, and there's still room for professional sensitivity.

Since January 20th, I have been involved in more than 10 days of epidemic reporting. The night before the closing of the city, I sent my family, my father-in-law, my mother-in-law and my children back to their hometown of Jingmen, Hubei Province, where Jingmen was also closed. The next morning, when the city was shut down, my wife and I rushed back to Wuhan. She didn't trust me. She said she would supervise me to do a good job of protection, and then she could take care of my life. She knows we're GONNA be busy.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
January 27th, after the siege, the empty bridge.

Round: What was the situation when you first came into contact with reports of a new coronavirus outbreak?

Chen Zhuo: we were a little scared of the virus at first. Because after all, SARS is so severe, you don't know what it will do to your body if you get infected. That's why there was no trip to the hospital. Later, through the People's Daily Online, CCTV and other relatively credible media, as well as some information released by the doctors who suffered from the disease, we learned that the disease has a greater impact on the elderly, especially some people who suffer from basic physical diseases, when the impact on young people was good, we relaxed a little bit, and then, under the arrangement of the newspaper, we went to the hospital and started reporting on the front lines.

As we do our regular reporting, we dig into the stories of front-line health care workers. For example, the first doctor to report the outbreak, Zhang Jixian, head of the respiratory department at the Hubei Provincial Hospital of traditional Chinese and Western medicine. We have interviewed and published some articles, which have aroused great social repercussions. For example, "a 120 emergency team Wuhan 12 hours, " such as some of the photo stories, as well as from the Community Epidemic Prevention Front report.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
##A 120 emergency squad in Wuhan for 12 hours

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
##How did she find out about this different kind of pneumonia when she first reported it

Zhang Jixian, director of respiratory and Critical Care Medicine Department of Hubei Integrated Traditional Chinese and Western Medicine Hospital. The outbreak was first detected in late December and was reported together with the hospital. From December 26 to 29,2019, he admitted seven patients with pneumonia. The chest radiograph showed that they were completely different from other viral pneumonia. Seven of them were similar, four from south China seafood. She quickly reported the situation to the hospital, which immediately reported it to the CDC in Kong Hon. December 29 reported to the provincial and Municipal Health Commission Disease Control Office. Provincial Health and Health Commission Disease Control Office instructed the Wuhan Center for Disease Control, Jinyintan Hospital and Kong Hon District Center for Disease Control, to start epidemiological investigations.

Mobilization of all fronts in Wuhan

Round: The situation has developed to this day, the discussion of various epidemic situations on the periphery is overwhelming. What was the mood and atmosphere around you when you were there?

Chen Zhuo: actually, after Academician Zhong Nanshan announced that the virus could be transmitted from person to person, the atmosphere in Wuhan became tense at once, and everyone responded to the announcement at their respective posts. For so many days on the front lines, the entire mobilization of Wuhan has been very, very extensive. All civil servants involved in epidemic prevention, whether at the municipal level, at the district level, at the street level, at the community level, including the commissariats of each bureau, are basically working overtime in their posts to do the prevention and control work within their capacity. Community isolation points have now been established to effectively isolate patients.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On January 27, Zhou Hong, a community worker, accompanied a suspected patient to the hospital for further examination and diagnosis.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
JN: What are some of the issues you see on the front line that need to be addressed?

Chen Zhuo: I think even though the focus is on immunization, there are a lot of groups that need to be addressed, like I'm doing a topic on parturient women. Wuhan has some hospitals to receive such pregnant women, because now public transport is closed, there are many people of love to organize a convoy to transfer these pregnant women to designated hospitals.

Ra: What was the scene that struck you the most during the filming?

Chen Zhuo: Most of the patients I work with are suspected cases, because it's a difficult disease to diagnose. What impressed me most was the mother who passed away. Her daughter's cry of "mother" was so heartbreaking. This kind of death of relatives, although we all experience, but when you really experience such a thing, it is really very, very difficult.

And the doctor, that kind of fearless professionalism, it's really very touching. During the Spring Festival, some doctors rarely go home and live in isolation wards. Sleep in a hospital or a designated hotel, or in a dorm room. Basically from before the Spring Festival, until now, have been working overtime, hard work, their spirit is very touching.

On February 4,2020, at 1:00 am, I felt sorry to see Zhang Dingyu, the director of the "gradually-frozen people" Hospital in Wuhan, dragging his trembling legs and hurrying to the scene of the isolation point in the living room of Wuhan

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
A nurse at 120 Puai Hospital in Wuhan answers a letter to her daughter and her family during the Spring Festival

Round: saw a Phoenix satellite TV special reporter was infected, including his parents. How do you keep yourselves safe during your reporting? How to deal with the contact and communication between family members?

Chen Zhuo: The reporter from ifeng.com, I don't know him, but as a colleague, I'm very concerned and very sympathetic. Indeed, journalists are on the front line almost every day, and the front-line epidemic prevention personnel, doctors, police contact, must do their own protection. Especially those colleagues who go to the hospital, after all, there are more patients.

When entering and leaving home, must use chlorine disinfection solution, or 84 disinfection water to their clothing, equipment disinfection, best body spray once when entering the door, and then wash hands immediately. If there are old people in the house, it is advised not to stay with them. Isolate yourself first, and if you're going to be reporting on the outbreak, it's best to wait until the whole thing is over before you meet your family. Now communication equipment is more developed, if you miss them, care about them, mobile video is very convenient. If they are short of supplies, it is recommended that when the purchase is returned, the items should be left at the door, and the outer packaging should be sprayed with chlorine-containing disinfectant or 84-degree water. You can also spray it with high-grade white wine and bring it in 20 minutes later.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
On the night of Jan. 28, a security guard used a loudspeaker to tell residents what to do about the COVID-19.

Record faithfully and do not allow yourself to become a pathogen

JN: You are a more experienced news photographer. How is this story different from the others?

Chen Zhuo: Some of the stories that we've been involved in, like the 2008 Sichuan Earthquake, the 2010 Gansu Mudslide, the sinking of the Oriental Star, they're all sudden events. This is really one of the more unfamiliar areas, that I've covered in my years of practice, public health events in the medical field. There's a lot of uncertainty in the interview, and you don't know where the virus is or when it's going to show up. That's the big difference, isn't it? An invisible danger.

Ro: How do you take a good picture in such a situation? Do you have any demands on yourself?

Chen Zhuo: I think a good news photo is an emotional photo. A cold onlooker, casually press the shutter, the photo will not move the reader. So be sure to capture the emotional moment of your subject. This interview doesn't require anything from you. Protect Yourself. Just protect your family from becoming a pathogen. Write faithfully. We don't know how long these days will last. Sometimes the mood is very down, it is not only an epidemic, from the overall perspective, the impact on the economy, especially the impact of private owners, but also for each of us ordinary people especially migrant workers. This year has been so hard!

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Private cars were banned from the city and downtown areas, and there were few cars on the empty Yingwuzhou Bridge. Only the white and blue ambulance, like the spirit of the night, brought light to the lonely city.
